<HEADLINE>
<P>
CHARGERS BULLY WAY TO 5-0 START 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By LONNIE WHITE, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 A very physical message was sent to the Kansas City Chiefs on Sunday: There is 
a new bully in the AFC West. 
</P>
<P>
 The message came in resounding fashion from the undefeated San Diego Chargers. 
</P>
<P>
 Behind the running of Natrone Means and a suffocating defensive front, the 
Chargers pounded Kansas City to remain the NFL's only undefeated team with a 
20-6 victory before 62,923 at Jack Murphy Stadium, the largest home crowd in 
Charger history. 
</P>
<P>
 After losing eight consecutive regular-season games to the Chiefs, San Diego 
made sure of its statement by dominating both sides of the ball while extending 
Kansas City's touchdown scoreless streak to eight quarters. 
</P>
<P>
 San Diego's biggest and most punishing weapon was Means, who ran for a 
career-high 125 yards in 19 carries. With his offensive line opening gaping 
holes, Means scored one touchdown and set up another as the Chargers averaged 
five yards a carry in gaining 151 yards. 
</P>
<P>
 "We had two weeks to kind of build this game up and it definitely had a 
playoff atmosphere," San Diego linebacker Junior Seau said. "I hope we kind of 
boosted our stock in the NFL to get the respect we deserve." 
</P>
<P>
 With a 5-0 record, the Chargers are off to their best start since 1961, when 
they finished 11-0 to win the AFL Western Division Championship. San Diego, 
which has defeated all four of its AFC West rivals, also moved two games ahead 
of the second-place Chiefs. 
</P>
<P>
 How thoroughly did the Chargers' defense dominate the line of scrimmage? 
</P>
<P>
 Kansas City quarterback Joe Montana's 55 pass attempts say it all. 
</P>
<P>
 Without a running game, Montana was forced to rely on short passes, completing 
37 for 310 yards, but was kept out of the end zone. 
</P>
<P>
 "At times he did look rattled," said Seau, who had a game-high 12 tackles. "We 
won the battle up front and we knew once we could get them to pass, we had them 
where we wanted." 
</P>
<P>
 Of Montana's 37 completions, 19 were to backs. Marcus Allen was his favorite, 
with nine catches for 83 yards. On the ground, however, Allen rushed for only 
17 yards in 10 carries. 
</P>
<P>
 "They made some good plays on runs," Montana said. "Those guys up front are 
pretty good." 
</P>
<P>
 The Chargers did not waste time taking control of the game by gaining good 
field position, something they have done well all season. 
</P>
<P>
 After taking the opening kickoff, San Diego drove to near midfield before 
punting, pinning the Chiefs back to their nine-yard line. 
</P>
<P>
 From there, the Charger defense took over, forcing Kansas City to punt after 
three plays. San Diego needed only 11 plays before John Carney kicked a 23-yard 
field goal for a 3-0 lead. 
</P>
<P>
 After Montana led the Chiefs on a 14-play, 63-yard drive at the start of the 
second quarter that tied the game on a 25-yard field goal by Lin Elliott, San 
Diego responded with scores on its next two possessions. 
</P>
<P>
 Carney kicked a 32-yarder to make it 6-3 after a 64-yard drive highlighted by 
a 48-yard pass play from Stan Humphries to Tony Martin. Following a Kansas City 
punt, the Chargers came right back behind Means, who carried five consecutive 
times before finishing the 43-yard drive with a nine-yard touchdown run. 
</P>
<P>
 In the third quarter, both teams struggled to move the ball as they combined 
to punt five times. The Chiefs managed only a 25-yard field goal by Elliott to 
begin the fourth quarter. 
</P>
<P>
 With a 13-6 lead and 13:02 remaining in the game, San Diego turned to Means 
again. The Chargers drove 77 yards in nine plays, with Means accounting for 57 
in four carries. 
</P>
<P>
 Humphries finished off the drive with a five-yard touchdown pass to wide 
receiver Mark Seay. 
</P>
<P>
 "Natrone had a great ball game," San Diego Coach Bobby Ross said. "He ran the 
ball extremely well. When we had to get it done in the fourth quarter, we had a 
good patented drive and most of it was on the ground." 
</P>
<P>
 Forced to play catch-up, Montana twice drove the Chiefs deep into San Diego 
territory in the final four minutes. Not only was he hurried on many of his 
throws but he also had several passes dropped. 
</P>
<P>
 "In my mind, the best team won," Kansas City Coach Marty Schottenheimer said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
