<HEADLINE>
<P>
COMMUNITY NEWS FOCUS: COSTA MESA; CAMPAIGN TO TARGET ABUSE AGAINST ELDERLY 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By TOM RAGAN 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 One out of every six persons over the age of 60 are abused, whether physically 
or emotionally, according to the Area Agency on Aging and Adult Protective 
Services in Orange County. 
</P>
<P>
 Operating on these statistics, the ARV Housing Group will start putting up 
billboards today around Costa Mesa, offering public workshops and distributing 
written material discussing the signs of elderly abuse, said Patti Barbee, the 
vice president of the group, which develops and manages affordable housing in 
the city of Costa Mesa. 
</P>
<P>
 "The saddest part in all the abuse is that only one out of every 14 cases are 
reported to authorities," Barbee said. "The victims usually suffer in silence." 
</P>
<P>
 The group will also provide free temporary housing for victims and make 
referrals to local senior service agencies, including the Area Agency on Aging 
and Adult Protective Services, which offers intervention programs on behalf of 
elder abuse victims. 
</P>
<P>
 The prevention campaign was announced last week at the company's annual "Mr. 
and Ms. Senior ARV" celebration, an annual event at the Costa Mesa Senior 
Center. The winners were Bill Welty, a resident of the company's Villa Bonita 
residence in San Diego, and Dottie Worthen, who resides at ARV's Villa de Palma 
in Placentia. 
</P>
<P>
 The company owns and operates nearly 40 residential care facilities, 
independent senior apartments and multifamily housing communities throughout 
the nation. TOM RAGAN 
</P>
</TEXT>
