<HEADLINE>
<P>
2 SUSPECTS ARRESTED IN ANAHEIM BURGLARY 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Aided by a police helicopter, two Los Angeles County men were arrested early 
Sunday on suspicion of burglarizing an Anaheim embroidery company, police said. 
</P>
<P>
 Mario Ruiz Lopez, 24, of Wilmington, and Fernando Lopez Estrada, 20, of 
Lynwood, were being held into Anaheim City Jail on suspicion of commercial 
burglary, said a spokesman for the Anaheim Police Department.Bail was set at 
$10,000 for each man. 
</P>
<P>
 The incident began at 1:40 a.m. when the pilots of Angel, the Anaheim police 
helicopter, apparently saw a suspicious vehicle parked in the commercial area 
of Pacific Embroidery Co., in the 1100 block of Kraemer Boulevard, according to 
a police statement. When the two men left the building and got into the car, 
the helicopter pilots tracked them to an area near Center Street and Melrose 
Avenue in Placentia, where they parked and fled on foot. 
</P>
<P>
 Anaheim police, with help from Fullerton and Placentia officers, found the men 
a short time later and arrested them without further incident, according to the 
report. No information was available on what was stolen. 
</P>
